Chimacum School District Meal Program Update
September 14, 2020

Through an extension of the USDA School Food Service waiver, we are able to offer free breakfast and lunch meals to ALL children in the community 18 and under until December 18, 2020. Meals are free regardless of income or enrollment.

When? Daily, Monday – Friday, 9:00-11:00 AM
Where? Pick up at the Multi-Purpose Building
(old Chimacum Elementary gym)

Meal bags contain breakfast and lunch for the day!

Note: All students who attend in-person classes may receive a free meal when at school and then pick up meals on remote days.

Thank You,
Chimacum School District
Food Service Department
(360) 302-5807

post_text:
Welcome to the 2020-2021 school year! I’m looking forward to learning more about the students, teachers, staff and families that make up this wonderful Chimacum community. I’m fortunate to have lived in Jefferson County now for nearly a decade. I’m hoping that my familiarity with the Quimper Peninsula communities of Port Townsend, Port Hadlock, Irondale and Chimacum stand me in good stead during this challenging time. Starting a new school year in the midst of a global pandemic is a test of our mettle and resolve! Chimacum’s talented teachers, staff, administrators and school board are working together to launch a meaningful and engaging program for the new school year. Whatever format the new school year takes, remote/online or hybrid/online, our community’s young people will be provided an educational experience that supports their continued growth and development. Please feel free to contact me at: david_engle@csd49.org

Best wishes for a great new school year,

Dr. David Engle
Acting Superintendent

Hello! We have several Chimacum School Board meetings scheduled this month: August 12, 19, 25, and 26. All meetings will be held remotely (Zoom) from 6:00 - 8:00 PM and are open to the public. Go to www.csd49.org the day of the meeting to find the Zoom link and view the agenda.

August 12th and 26th are considered regular meetings.

The Chimacum School Board will vote on the 2020-21 reopening plans on August 19th.

August 25th, the Chimacum and Port Townsend School Boards will hold a collaborative meeting, facilitated by our Acting Superintendent, David Engle.

Please join us!

Message from Superintendent Rick Thompson
June 24, 2020

Dear Chimacum Families:

Our school district is reviewing three models for the return to school in the fall.

We would appreciate your input as we create the best plan for our students, staff, and families.

Health department guidance is at the forefront of our decision making and will be strongly considered in any model we choose.

Return to school guidance has been provided by the Office of Superintendent of Public Instruction at www.k12.wa.

Please take a few moments to complete the survey below:
https://docs.google.com/forms/d/1i0GXkNN7G1wOpLYRXqHlK1YjY0IEMbxb7k1IX6EWEyM/edit?ts=5ef2bd43

The survey closes on Friday, July 3, 2020.

We thank you for your time.

Rick Thompson
Superintendent
(360) 302-5896
rick_thompson@csd49.org

post_text:
Message from CJSH Counselor, Barb Fogerson:

PLU has decided to offer a set of general college knowledge zoom webinars throughout the summer for any high school student interested, but we are particularly targeting rising juniors and seniors.

We are calling it 'Suit Up for your Senior Year' and here are the topics:
• June 4 - The College Search Process 101: Where do I start?
• June 18 - College Applications 101: How to Land in the 'Yes' Pile
• July 2 - College Essay 101: Tips & Tricks
• July 16 - Financial Aid & Scholarships 101: Paying for College
• July 30 - College Bound Scholarship 101: Use your scholarship to its fullest
• August 13 - Running Start to 4-years 101: A University's Perspective
More information and to register for one or all of them: https://www.plu.edu/admission/important-dates/suit-up/

"PLU seeks to educate students for lives of thoughtful inquiry, service, leadership,
and care for others, for the community, and for the earth."

Dear Chimacum Students and Families,

We have set up a plan to help facilitate getting all our library and textbooks back in a safe and efficient way for everyone.

The following schedule for grades 3 – 12 is a suggestion to keep our numbers down. If the date does not work for your family for any reason, please feel free to come by on a day that does works for you. We would like to support you in this process.

We will be carefully following social distancing guidelines to keep our staff, students and community safe.

If you have any questions, please don't hesitate to contact me at (360) 302-5979 or michele_moriarty@csd49.org.

Thank you,
Michele Moriarty
Library Media Specialist K-12

Textbook and Library Book Return Schedule

Location: CJSHS Commons (outside tent)
Time: 9-2 pm
Staff: Cris Taylor will be there to help you!

Monday, June 1: 12th grade
Tuesday, June 2: 12th and 11th grade
Wednesday, June 3: 12th and 10th grade
Thursday, June 4: 12 and 9th grade
Friday, June 5: 12th and 7/8th grade

M-F, June 8-12 & 15-19: 3-12 grades

Spring break is coming up next week, April 6 - 10, so our meal delivery and pick-up service is shifting to give our employees that time off.

We will *not* be delivering food on Friday, April 3rd or Tuesday-Friday, April 7th-10th.

Instead, we're providing 2 days worth of food and milk on Thursday, April 2nd, and 5 days worth of food and milk on Monday, April 6th.

Pick-up times and locations remain the same. Bus route stops and times remain the same.

We ask all parents to accompany their children to the pick-up locations and bus stops so they may be available to help the children carry the bags/boxes of food.

Questions? Please call: Food Service at (360) 302-5807, Transportation at (360) 302-5812, or District Office at (360) 302-5891. Thank you!

Good afternoon,

Chimacum School District was alerted this morning that two of our students had been exposed to COVID-19 also known as the Coronavirus. The Health Department was contacted and the situation was presented to them. The Health Department contacted the family and discussed the situation with the parent. It was reported back to the district, by the Health Department, that students do not have any symptoms at this time and it is believed they are currently not contagious. The students were picked up and are not at school. In addition, we are notifying you as a precautionary measure and want you to know we are watching the situation closely.

Please know we will update our employees, parents, students, and community as we get new information or need to take action.

Attached is additional information about COVID-19 and links to several websites for the most up to date information.

Sincerely,
Rick Thompson

post_text:
CHIMACUM F.E.E.D. PROGRAM
Chimacum High School students in the Foods and Horticulture classes will have the opportunity this spring to learn more about the local food system from a series of lectures and discussions offered by a range of regional agricultural enterprises, advocates and community organizations, including Jefferson Historical Society, Jefferson Land Trust, Jefferson Healthcare, Chimacum Corner Farmstand, Finnriver Farm, Jefferson County 4H, Jefferson County Farmers Markets, the PT Food Coop and more.

This series is coordinated by the Community Wellness Project and by Chimacum teachers as part of the F.E.E.D. program (Food Education & Entrepreneurial Development) — designed to expand student awareness of and meaningful engagement with the local agricultural community and economy. The F.E.E.D. program has the long term goal of working with Chimacum Schools to create a student-operated value-added food enterprise that will teach business development and enterprise management skills, and serve as a professional skills incubator and job placement service.

post_text:
Message from CJSH Counselor, Barb Fogerson
Due to inclement weather the Puget Sound Naval Shipyard presentation is rescheduled for January 24 at 11:40 a.m.

Event Details:
Chimacum Jr/Sr High school is hosting a presentation from the Puget Sound Naval Shipyard & Intermediate Maintenance Facility on Friday, January 24 at 11:40 am. The presenter will cover information about the Work Study Program. This program is an Introductory Industrial Trades Rotation Program designed for high school juniors on track to meet high school graduation requirements. The program is also open to post-secondary students enrolled in trades-related certificate or degree programs. Students who are accepted into this program participate in full time work (40 hours per week) for the summer between their junior year and senior year and one semester of their senior year. To learn more about this program and how to apply you will want to attend this presentation. Please sign up in the Jr/Sr High School counseling office if you would like to attend.

https://www.navy.mil/local/PSNS/

Students 10th-12th grade – We are offering the ASVAB at Chimacum Jr/Sr High on Dec 2nd.

The ASVAB (Armed Services Vocational Aptitude Battery) is the most widely used multiple-aptitude test battery in the world. As an aptitude test, the ASVAB measures your strengths, weaknesses, and potential for future success. The ASVAB also provides you with career information for various civilian and military occupations and is an indicator for success in future endeavors whether you choose to go to college, vocational school, or a military career. No military obligation is required.

The ASVAB is Free. Sign up in the counseling office by November 27th if you want to take the ASVAB. Space is limited.

Questions, please contact:
Terri Brewer
Admin Assistant/Registrar
Chimacum Jr/Sr High School
terri_brewer@csd49.org
(360) 302-5906

Chef Kent Getzin Consulting: Creative Culinary Solutions
November 5, 2019 at 11:03 AM ·

Last Thursday and Friday I had the opportunity to make some delicious food with the Food Service team from Chimacum Schools (near Port Townsend, WA)!The two days of training focused on how to incorporate more whole foods and scratch cooking into their school menus! We learned about taste physiology and how our tongues sense flavors, and we learned ways to build flavors using both culinary techniques and tasty ingredients. We also discussed how to build world flavors to make scratch food kids can't wait to eat! Let's talk about this type of training in your district!

District Coordinator: Jamie Jensen
Contact: (360) 302-5959 or jamie_jensen@csd49.org

Details: In accordance with state legislation, the focus for our K-12 Highly Capable Program is to meet the individual needs of our advanced students all day every day! The Highly Capable Coordinator collaborates with classroom teachers and provides enrichment opportunities such as the Young Writer's Conference, UW Engineering Discovery Days, etc.

Our main identification activities take place during the Spring and Fall of each year. Students new to the district may be nominated at any time.

If you would like to nominate a student for the Highly Capable Program, visit www.csd49.org, click on Programs & Resources, then Highly Capable. Look for the link to download the Parent Nomination Packet.

Note: We are currently accepting nominations for the 2020/21 school year.

post_text:
Team Educate-Oars invites you all to a gathering/fundraiser at Finnriver on Wednesday, May 15th from 5-7pm to support a wonderful group educators modeling perseverance, teamwork, dedication and grit for their students and community!

There are eleven Educators-Oars from Chimacum Public School District, who, with very little previous experience rowing a long dory, are participating in a seventy mile, human-powered rowing race from Tacoma to Port Townsend called the Seventy48.

Race day is May 31st! With the support of the Community Boat Project, Chimacum students built the boat they will be rowing.

The team is excited to be out there sharing how awesome their students and community are! Along with covering basic registration fees for the race, the team will donate any additional funds raised to the Community Boat Project.

“Practicing & counting down the days! Seventy48 is almost upon us!
Team Educate-Oars has a pretty cool story, (just like our competition we’re sure)! The long dory Dragonheart was built at our local ‘Community Boat Project’ in Port Hadlock, by our students. Celebrating Inspiration & Community Leadership! WASA Region 114 Awards – April 15, 2019

"It certainly takes an entire community to service, harness, and showcase the qualities that make each school district unique." - WASA

Chimacum Superintendent Rick Thompson recognized Piper Diehl, Kelly Liske, Staci Matthes, and Nikki Casal for their infinite hours of volunteer time, inspirational ideas and programs for students, and ongoing support of the Chimacum School District.

HELP WANTED: SUBSTITUTE BUS DRIVERS

Transportation is seeking substitute school bus drivers –
Make a difference in the life of a child! Become a trained and licensed school bus driver and earn extra money in your spare time.

Do you enjoy being around young people? Do you have a clean driving record? Are you self-employed, retired or a stay at home parent? This position is right for you!

Pick your shift: mornings, afternoons, every other day; just about any configuration is possible. You are off when your children or grandchildren are off.

You can earn from $15.80 to $17.70 per hour. We will pay for your expenses up to $485.00 toward your Commercial
Driver License, after completion of 200 hours of drive time on routes as a substitute.

Are you interested? Have any questions?
Contact Transportation Director Monica Mulligan at (360) 302-5812 or monica_mulligan@csd49.org.

To apply, go to www.cdd49.org and click on Employment.

post_text:
Dear Parents, Staff and Community Members,

This past fall we invited our community to share their thoughts about what we are doing well, and where we can improve as a District.

Our goal was to get a sense of shared values from our schools and community. We were excited to learn more about the priorities that were voiced for the Chimacum School District.

We have reviewed the results and shared them with our committee, in order to expand on what we heard we were doing well and to create new educational opportunities.

To view the results of the exchange, go to:
http://csd49.thoughtexchange.com/september-2018/

Your feedback is vital to our plans for the future. If you were one of the many people that participated, we thank you for taking the time to contribute your thoughts and priorities.

Sincerely,

Rick Thompson
Superintendent

post_text:
A message from Chimacum Schools Food Service department:

Due to changes in the House Bill 2610, as of March 7, 2018, no school or school personnel may inform students under the age of 15 of a negative balance to their food service account. The student's parent or guardian will be sent a letter or receive a phone call no later than 10 days after the first negative balance.

If you believe your family may qualify for free or reduced school meals, please fill out an application. The application may be found under the Food Services department page at http://www.csd49.org/Content2/48. Applications are also available at any of the school offices or the District Office.

Parents or guardians can keep track of their child's balance by way of Skyward Family Access, which you may reach by clicking on the "Skyward" button located near the top right side of the website page. Please contact your child's school office to learn more about Skyward Family Access.

The Community Wellness Project is sponsoring a Harvest Dinner and Dessert Auction, and you're invited! Please join us October 25th, 5:30 - 8:30 pm at Finnriver. This festive all-ages celebration of food and community will feature a locally sourced menu prepared and served by PT Foods Services Director Stacey Larson, and students and staff from the culinary and foods programs in both districts. The evening will include kid's activities, special guests, and a dessert auction featuring treats from some of our community's favorite culinary artists. Tickets are limited; $35 per person, $10 for students, kids 5 and under eat free. Buy your tickets today.

Please help us spread the word to friends and colleagues. We can't wait to share a meal together and celebrate progress. Hope to see you there!

In Gratitude,
Shelby Smith
Board Member, Community Wellness Project
